            "summary": "Quantum computing firm Project Eleven has launched the \"Q-Day Prize\" competition offering 1 Bitcoin (BTC) to whoever cracks the biggest chunk of a Bitcoin key using a quantum computer within the next year. More than 6 million BTC, worth around $500 billion, could be at risk if quantum computers crack elliptic curve cryptography (ECC) keys. The winner has until April 5, 2026 to win the prize. Current estimates suggest around 2,000 logical qubits would be needed to break a 256-bit ECC key, with IBM and Google's current qubit capabilities causing concern. Bitcoiners are divided on the urgency of the quantum threat, with some stating there's still time to find quantum-proof solutions. Jameson Lopp believes the industry should begin discussing the issue seriously. Tether CEO Paolo Ardoino is confident that quantum-proof Bitcoin addresses will be implemented before any serious threat emerges.",
